  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Lush Tropical Island</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Curaçao is arid, with cacti and dry landscapes. It's beautiful but different from lush islands like Jamaica or Costa Rica. If you expect tropical jungle, you'll be surprised.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Everyone Speaks English</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While English is common in tourist areas, Dutch and Papiamentu are primary languages. Some Spanish helps too. Learn a few phrases in Papiamentu to connect with locals.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting About Car Rental</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Curaçao isn't very walkable outside Willemstad center. Most nomads need a car to explore beaches and dive sites. Budget for rental or consider buying if staying long-term.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Evacuation Coverage</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While basic healthcare is good, complex cases need evacuation. Make sure your insurance includes medical evacuation to Colombia, US, or Netherlands.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Exploring Beyond Willemstad</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Willemstad is charming but the whole island offers amazing beaches, diving spots, and experiences. Get out and explore—Shete Boka National Park, Playa Kenepa, and more await.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Curaçao -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Curaçao</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare in Curaçao meets Dutch standards for basic care. The main hospital handles most needs, with evacuation available for complex cases.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Facilities</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Curaçao Medical Center (CMC)</strong> - Main hospital in Willemstad, Dutch-standard care</li>
      <li><strong>St. Elisabeth Hospital</strong> - Secondary facility</li>
      <li><strong>Various private clinics</strong> - GP and specialist services</li>
      <li><strong>Dental clinics</strong> - Good availability</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Sample Costs (Without Insurance)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> $50-80</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> $80-150</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency room:</strong> $150-400</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital stay:</strong> $500-1,000/day</li>
      <li><strong>Dental cleaning:</strong> $60-100</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Dutch connection:</strong> For Dutch citizens, some healthcare benefits may transfer. Check with SVB (social insurance) about coverage in Curaçao as part of the Kingdom of the Netherlands.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is Curaçao outside the hurricane belt?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Curaçao sits far south in the Caribbean, below where hurricanes typically form and travel. While not 100% immune, the island very rarely experiences hurricanes, making it one of the safest Caribbean destinations weather-wise.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What language should I learn?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          English works in tourist areas, but Papiamentu (local Creole) and Dutch are primary. Spanish is also widely understood. Learning basic Papiamentu phrases will endear you to locals. "Bon dia" (good day) and "Danki" (thank you) go far.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need a car?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Strongly recommended. While Willemstad center is walkable, the best beaches, dive sites, and experiences require transportation. Public transit is limited. Most nomads rent or buy a car.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How's the internet?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Internet is decent in Curaçao—50-100 Mbps available in most areas. The Dutch infrastructure means more reliable than some Caribbean islands. Verify speeds before committing to accommodation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's special about the diving?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Curaçao is famous for shore diving—60+ sites accessible directly from shore, no boat needed. The underwater world features coral gardens, sea turtles, and excellent visibility. Many nomads choose Curaçao specifically for diving.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I extend beyond 6 months?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, the initial 6-month stay can typically be extended. Requirements may include showing continued income and valid insurance. Longer residence permit options exist for those wanting to stay years.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

